title: Human reproductive technology council established
content_text: The Government published in the Gazette today (May 25) the establishment of a human reproductive technology council to regulate the conduct of reproductive technology in accordance with the Human Reproductive Technology Ordinance enacted by the Legislative Council in June last year. The Council on Human Reproductive Technology is chaired by Dr Leong Chi-hung. It consists of 21 members from a wide cross-section of the community, such as medical and legal professions, social worker, theologist, scholar in philosophy or ethics, psychiatrists or psychologist, sociologist, and government representatives. Welcoming

government representatives. Welcoming
the establishment of the council, Dr Leong said today (May 25) that with
most members having served in the Provisional Council, efficiency and
continuity of work could be ensured. He
stressed that the setting up of the council would provide a mechanism for
on-going monitoring of various existing and future reproductive technology
activities in Hong Kong for the benefit of all parties involved, in
particular the welfare of the children born out of such technologies. One of
the major functions of the council is to vet applications for licence to

the major functions of the council is to vet applications for licence to
carry out human reproductive technology activities, and to issue a Code of
Practice to the involved personnels. Dr Leong
said, "I hope that the Government would expedite the legislative
process for the corresponding and relevant regulations, so that the
council can actually start our work without delay. "Yet,
even before then, we would finalize the Code of Practice as soon as
possible for voluntary compliance. I am confident that those well-intended
institutions will be more than willing to comply, even before it is made

institutions will be more than willing to comply, even before it is made
into law, for the benefit of the clients they serve. "Human
reproductive technology advances by leaps and bounds. Our council will
react and install monitoring procedures promptly to cope with any new
advances, as empowered by law," Dr Leong added. The
